","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Boye","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Olivier.  Scandinavian Erik.","North German and Danish: from an ancient Germanic personal name, <i>Boio</i>, possibly meaning ‘boy’ (see   Boy   1) or, alternatively, representing a variant of   Bothe  , with the regular Low German loss of the dental between vowels. This surname is also found in Norway and Sweden. Compare   Boie  .","English: variant of   Boy  , a cognate of 1 above."],"variants":[{"name":"Boykin","meanings":["English: from a pet form of the Middle English personal name   Boye  .","History: Jarvis Boykin was one of the free planters who assented to the‘Fundamental Agreement’ of the New Haven Colony on June 4, 1639."]},{"name":"Beu","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto, Wolfgang.","North German:","variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boysen","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Gerd, Hans, Erwin, Hermann, Juergen, Lorenz, Siegfried.","North German, Danish, and Norwegian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boie","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Camille, Emile, Fernand.","North German and Danish: variant of   Boye  .","Americanized form of French   Bois  ."]},{"name":"Bey","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Arabic/Muslim Mohammed, Abdullah, Dawoud, Fatima, Jamaal, Rasheedah, Shakoor, Zaib, Aisha, Akil, Ameen, Aminah.","North German and Dutch: from the personal name <i>Beye</i> or <i>Baye</i>, vowel variants of   Boye  .","Germanized form of Sorbian <b>Baj</b>: nickname or occupational name from Upper Sorbian <i>baj</i> ‘storyteller’. Compare   Bay  ."]},{"name":"Boje","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Goetz, Johannes.","German: variant of   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boyens","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Georg.","North German and North Frisian: patronymic from the personal name   Boye  ."]},{"name":"Boy","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Hans Peter, Heinz, Horst.","English: from the Middle English personal name <i>Boie</i>, which may be from ancient Germanic <i>Boio</i> (see   Boye   1 and 2) or an Old English <i>Boia</i>. The latter is common as a first element in English placenames, and is difficult to tell apart from the ordinary word <i>boy</i>, to which it may be related.","English: from Middle English <i>boy</i> ‘young man, servant’, also ‘knave’ or ‘rogue’. Compare   Ladd  ."]},{"name":"Boykins","meanings":["Americanized form of Dutch <b>Boeijkens</b>: patronymic from the personal name   Boye   with the diminutive element <i>-ken</i> and genitive <i>-s</i>. Compare the English cognate   Boykin   and North German   Boyken  ."]}]},{"name":"Mary","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Variant of   Màiri ."],"variants":[{"name":"Màiri","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Mary</b> ."]}]},{"name":"Agnes","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Latinized version of the Greek name <i>Hagnē</i>, from the feminine form of the adjective <i>hagnos</i> ‘pure, holy’. This was the name of a young Roman virgin martyred in the persecutions instigated by the Roman emperor Diocletian in   ad  303 . She became a very popular saint in the Middle Ages. Her name was early associated with Latin <i>agnus</i> ‘lamb’, leading to the consistent dropping of the initial <i>H-</i> and to her representation in art accompanied by a lamb. The colloquial form <i>Annes</i> led to some confusion with <i>Ann(e)</i> in earlier centuries. Frequent in the medieval period, the name was revived in the 19th century, and has been especially popular in Scotland.  See also  Annis ."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mary Agnes Boye was born in 1408, in Sydenham, Somerset, England, her father, Sir William Boye, was 27 and her mother, Alice Boye, was 23. She married John Cox in 1427, in Sydenham, Somerset, England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 4 sons and 1 daughter. She died in 1447, at the age of 39."},"et":{"1408–1447":"1408–1447","1408–1465":"1408–1465","1430–1507":"1430–1507","1434–1507":"1434–1507","1435–1501":"1435–1501","1447–1497":"1447–1497","–1500":"–1500","1382–Male":"1382–Surnud","1386–Female":"1386–Surnud","1382":"1382","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1434":"1434","1465":"1465","1497":"1497","1386":"1386","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1507":"1507","about 1430":"umbes 1430","8 June 1434":"8. juuni 1434","1427":"1427","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales, United Kingdom","Warwickshire, England":"Warwickshire, England"},"fi":{"1408–1447":"1408–1447","1408–1465":"1408–1465","1430–1507":"1430–1507","1434–1507":"1434–1507","1435–1501":"1435–1501","1447–1497":"1447–1497","–1500":"–1500","1382–Male":"1382–Kuollut","1386–Female":"1386–Kuollut","1382":"1382","1447":"1447","1435":"1435","1501":"1501","1500":"1500","1434":"1434","1465":"1465","1497":"1497","1386":"1386","1430":"1430","1408":"1408","1507":"1507","about 1430":"noin 1430","8 June 1434":"8. kesäkuuta 1434","1427":"1427","Sydenham, Somerset, England":"Sydenham, Somerset, Englanti, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Bristol, Gloucestershire, England":"Bristol, Gloucestershire, England","Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales":"Skenfrith, Monmouthshire, Wales, Yhdistynyt kuningaskunta","Warwickshi